\section{Introduction}
\setcounter{page}{1}

% 1
All health systems must set priorities in order to allocate scarce fiscal, personnel, and medical resources. Rationing occurs when potentially beneficial interventions are withheld from individuals (Scheunemann and White 2011). It is inherently political and marked by moral and ethical dilemmas, alongside conflicting values and interests \parencite{BaeroeBaltussen2014LegitimateLimitSetting, Baltussen2016PrioritySettingUHC}. Funding decisions of novel, high-cost medicines exemplify the societal tensions involved, often surfacing as debates in the media \parencite{AbelsonCollins2009MediaHypingHerceptin, CorbettMori1999MedicineMediaCelebrities}.
In this article, we provide experimental evidence on how citizens’ support for public funding of a novel cancer medicine varies depending on how the decision is framed. Previous research suggests that societal preferences regarding high-cost medications are susceptible to emotionally charged narratives circulated through mass media, which can, in turn, shape political decision-making \parencite{Gabe2012HerceptinCountervailingPowers, Aggarwal2017CancerDrugsFund, PinhoDiasCosta2020MassMediaObstacleRationing}.

% 2
We examine whether preferences over healthcare funding decisions remain elastic to framing effects even when these decisions are insulated from partisan politics and are not presented through individual patient stories. By institutional insulation, we refer to the delegation of contentious 
reimbursement decisions to specialized agencies formally distinct from  politicians, tasked with employing technical methods such as health technology 
assessment (HTA) to depoliticize and objectify decision-making 
\parencite{EgebergTrondal2009Agencification, Thatcher2002}. In democracies with publicly funded healthcare systems, politics is the arena in which the values guiding prioritisation and rationing are debated, yet these institutional arrangements are envisaged to depoliticise decision-making \parencite{Thatcher2002}. To assess whether institutional insulation neutralises framing effects, we field a survey experiment embedded in the 2021 Finnish Medicines Barometer in which we randomly vary the interpretive frame attached to an otherwise identical reimbursement decision. This design allows us to test a core finding from prospect theory \parencite{Kahneman1979}: that individuals evaluate options relative to a reference point, creating systematic framing effects where identical choices are treated differently depending on how they are presented (as gains or losses). We examine whether these reference-dependent framing effects persist when citizens evaluate healthcare rationing decisions through delegated expert institutions. Specifically, we test whether varying the interpretive frame of an otherwise identical reimbursement decision produces framing effects even in institutional contexts designed to depoliticize decision-making. This allows us to assess whether public interpretation remains consequential for preference formation and policy legitimacy even in expert-driven settings. %This question is relevant because these decisions are often more complex than many other political decisions: technical complexity and confidentiality can distance reimbursement processes from qualities associated with legitimacy \parencite{BarrenhoLopert2022PriceTransparencyOECD, Mitton2006CentralizedDrugReviewFairness, KapiririRazavi2017SystematicPrioritySetting, DanielsSabin2008AccountabilityUpdate, DanielsVanDerWilt2016HTADeliberative}, while expert rationales rather than individual patient narratives typically structure how such choices are justified in public debate.

% 3
We argue that institutional insulation does not neutralise framing effects in mass preferences because it does not alter the cognitive mechanisms through which citizens evaluate distributive trade-offs. Instead, delegation shifts political contestation toward the realm of public interpretation. When citizens encounter decisions justified on technical or clinical grounds, the interpretive frame sets the reference point against which outcomes are judged---in this case, shaping whether distributive restraint is understood as prudent health maximisation or as an avoidable loss.

% 4
Our findings have important implications for policy. First, decisions on funding cancer medicines are increasingly challenged by the lack of robust clinical evidence, a consequence of policies that prioritise accelerated access of novel therapies \parencite{Hwang2020ExpeditedApprovalTherapeuticValue, VellaBonanno2017AdaptivePathways, Cohen2017CancerDrugsHighPrice, Davis2017EvidenceCancerDrugsEMA, Brinkhuis2024AddedBenefitRevenues}. Public and third-party payers must therefore decide on coverage despite limited data on health gains and safety, yet with full certainty of extraordinary costs \parencite{Cohen2017CancerDrugsHighPrice}. Second, mass preferences play a key role in welfare state legitimacy. Public perceptions of acceptability or fairness, and influence political trust, willingness to pay taxes, confidence in the health system, and the uptake of supplementary private insurance as a response to perceived access failures. Finally, the framing approach offers us important insights to institutional feedback mechanisms and democratic decision-making. It both helps decision-makers to communicate more clearly about the reasoning behind difficult choices and provide insight into how different stakeholders, including commercial actors, advocacy groups, and policymakers, may use framing to advance their positions \parencite{Greer2016StrengtheningGovernance}.

% 5
Understanding the elasticity of mass preferences is essential for navigating how citizens interpret complex funding decisions. It can help public payers communicate more clearly about the reasoning behind difficult choices, while also providing insight into how different stakeholders, including commercial actors, advocacy groups, and policymakers, may use framing to advance their positions \parencite{Greer2016StrengtheningGovernance, PinhoDiasCosta2020MassMediaObstacleRationing}. 


This paper proceeds as follows. In \Cref{values} we review the core principles and contested value trade-offs that structure healthcare priority setting and, in turn, supply the normative content for competing justifications of rationing decisions. In \Cref{theory} we develop the theoretical argument, specifying how prospect theory and the rule of rescue generate reference-point-dependent evaluations of high-cost reimbursement decisions under technocratic delegation. Next, \Cref{empirics} describes the survey experiment embedded in the 2021 Finnish Medicines Barometer, including the framing manipulation and the empirical strategy used to estimate framing effects (\Cref{eq:ordinal_model}). We then present the results, reporting covariate balance (\Cref{fig:summary}) and model-based predicted probabilities across experimental conditions (\Cref{fig:pred}). In \Cref{discussion} we offer some implications for the legitimacy and contestability of expert-justified rationing decisions in publicly funded healthcare systems.


\subsection{Values underpinning priority setting in healthcare}\label{values}

Rationing inevitably involves value judgements, which may be explicit or implicit, either stated directly or embedded within assessment procedures \parencite{ClarkWeale2012SocialValuesPrioritySetting}. For example, HTA frequently includes cost-effectiveness or cost-utility analysis as an evaluation method. The choice of such methods already reflects a normative commitment to health maximisation as the guiding prioritisation principle \parencite{Jansen2017FairProcessesPrioritySetting, DanielsVanDerWilt2016HTADeliberative}.

Prioritisation principles refer to judgements that reflect societal values, that is, moral or ethical values of the society in question \parencite{ClarkWeale2012SocialValuesPrioritySetting}. For prioritisation to be legitimate, it must embody the values held by the population affected. Both the processes through which rationing decisions are made and the content of those decisions involve value judgements. The principles applied---whether economic, clinical, or related to personal characteristics, deservingness, or merit---remain widely contested and context dependent, making it difficult, if not impossible, to identify a single, overarching rule that would be accepted by all stakeholders \parencite{Oliver2009FairTestFairInnings, Watters2016FairInningsEmpiricalPerspective}.

The overall value base of the European health systems, and the welfare states they are embedded, is grounded in solidarity and institutionalised as charters and legislation that ensure social rights. In healthcare, access, equity, quality, performance and efficiency have been proposed as the core principles through which European health systems pursue a fair distribution of resources \parencite{EuropeanCommission2019DefiningValueVBHC}. Values linked with legitimate decision-making processes include, for example, publicity, relevance, revisability, and enforceability \parencite{Daniels2000AccountabilityReasonableness, DanielsVanDerWilt2016HTADeliberative}.

The focus of this article is, however, on values related to the content of decision-making (what decisions are made and why). Commonly applied values in healthcare prioritisation include clinical effectiveness and cost effectiveness \parencite{ClarkWeale2012SocialValuesPrioritySetting}. These aim to direct scarce resources to interventions most likely to generate health gains, thereby producing the greatest possible health for the population (health maximisation). The concept of opportunity cost refers to the foregone benefits associated with the next-best alternative, implying that resources invested in one intervention necessarily reduce what can be achieved elsewhere \parencite{Maguire2023}. The application of these criteria depends on the availability of high quality evidence of clinical value. Furthermore, cost effectiveness is typically assessed through complex and technical evaluations of health benefits (e.g., Quality Adjusted Life Years, QALYs) and costs, with the aim of comparing the relative worth of different interventions. Although widely used, QALY concept involves controversial value judgements \parencite{Dukhanin2018IntegratingSocialJustice, Mahdiani2024QALYStillQALY, Andrade2025EthicalShortcomingsQALY}.

Social justice and equity considerations include the concepts of horizontal and vertical equity \parencite{ODonnell2008AnalyzingHealthEquity}. In healthcare, this implies that people with similar conditions, or conditions of similar severity, should be treated in the same way, while people with differing levels of disease severity should receive differential treatment according to their respective needs. Controversy arises when determining which personal characteristics are relevant to assessing those needs \parencite{ClarkWeale2012SocialValuesPrioritySetting}. Are people of different ages, family structures, societal contributions, life expectancies, or lifestyle choices treated differently, or are such characteristics deemed irrelevant? For instance, the ‘fair innings’ intuition reflects preferences that view older people as already having enjoyed more life years than younger individuals, thereby prioritising the young so they too may be given the opportunity for a similar lifespan \parencite{Oliver2009FairTestFairInnings, Watters2016FairInningsEmpiricalPerspective, Adler2025FairInnings}.

Health maximisation criterion also clashes with peoples’ intuitive ‘rule of rescue’ obligation to save individuals from imminent death at any cost, even when those costs could be used more efficiently elsewhere \parencite{Cookson2008RuleOfRescue, Sinclair2022a, Andrade2025EthicalShortcomingsQALY}. The ‘rule of rescue’ has been attributed to preferences for identifiable patients, although it appears to apply more broadly \parencite{McKie2003, Sinclair2022a}. One explanation centers on narrative considerations: people may be averse to letting others die suddenly, without the opportunity to settle their affairs, say goodbye, and come to terms with death \parencite{Sinclair2022a}.


Payers have attempted to incorporate social justice and ‘rule of rescue’ considerations into the assessment criteria through various methods \parencite{Cookson2008RuleOfRescue, Dukhanin2018IntegratingSocialJustice, Mahdiani2024QALYStillQALY}. Proportional or absolute shortfall methods seek to account for disease severity \parencite{Mahdiani2024QALYStillQALY} while end-of-life premiums allow relaxed cost-per-QALY thresholds for treatments expected to extend the lives of patients close to death \parencite{Olofsson2018EndOfLifePremiumCancer}. Nevertheless, even relaxed criteria require some evidence of added months, weeks or even days of life. Yet from the perspective of a severely ill patient and their family, it may be profoundly important that something, anything, is done, regardless of high levels of uncertainty about whether the intervention is beneficial or even harmful \parencite{ClarkWeale2012SocialValuesPrioritySetting, MacLeod2016HighCostCancerDrugsReview}. Consequently, patients and citizens seem far less willing to accept any prioritisation based on cost than payers \parencite{MacLeod2016HighCostCancerDrugsReview}. Furthermore, application of ‘rule of rescue’ as funding criteria has created concerns over the ‘fetishisation of technology,’ meaning the prioritising of making technologies available to all human conditions at the expense of population health \parencite{Cookson2008RuleOfRescue}.

Mass preferences related to public funding of cancer medicines are also likely influenced by peoples’ perceptions of cancer. Intuitively, people tend to associate cancer with fear of imminent death, although this is often followed by a more deliberate recognition of improvements in care and increasing survival rates \parencite{Robb2014PublicPerceptionsCancer}. Willingness to pay, and reluctance to reduce spending, tends to be high for cancer care compared with many other conditions \parencite{Morrell2017PublicPreferHealthGainCancer, Schomerus2006PreferencesCutbacks}. However, this may reflect priority based on severity intuitively attached to cancer rather than specific preference for cancer itself, as evidence does not consistently support higher preference for cancer over other conditions of similar severity \parencite{Morrell2017PublicPreferHealthGainCancer}.

Empiric studies on public values suggest that societal willingness to pay decreases with patients’ age and increases with perceived disease severity \parencite{Gu2015AttributesWeightsPrioritySetting, Loupas2026WTPperQALYSystematicReview}. Willingness to pay is high for the treatment of rare diseases despite high medical costs, although, there is no evidence of a clear preference for rare over common diseases \parencite{Gu2023RareCommonDiseases}. Lower priority also appears to be given to people with self-induced conditions or higher socioeconomic positions \parencite{Gu2015AttributesWeightsPrioritySetting, BauteBellani2025HealthcareDeservingness}. The public tends to view individuals engaging in risky behaviours as less deserving of publicly financed healthcare and values preventive services for lifestyle-related conditions less than those targeting genetic disorders \parencite{Singh2012ResponsibilityValuationHealthcare}. Larger health gains tend to be prioritised over smaller gains, and life extensions over quality-of-life improvement, although evidence regarding end-of-life premiums is mixed, possibly due to sensitivity to framing effects \parencite{Gu2015AttributesWeightsPrioritySetting, Morrell2017PublicPreferHealthGainCancer}. Opportunity costs are often neglected in personal consumption decisions, yet experimental evidence suggests that making them more salient exerts a small but robust effect on choice \parencite{Maguire2023}.

While these studies help to illuminate public values, they are prone to bias, and it remains debatable whether, and to what extent, they should guide the selection of principles for priority setting \parencite{Whitty2014StatedPreferencePrioritySetting, GustavssonLindblom2025JustificationPrinciplesPriority}. This is particularly relevant when mass preferences conflict with human and/or social rights (e.g. racist preferences). Deservingness opinions are also shaped by individuals’ level of understanding of the topic, which may explain why the public and policymakers often prioritise different values. Citizens’ views may be more influenced by simple deservingness heuristics, while policymakers more familiar with the issues tend to consider a broader array of perspectives in their decisions \parencite{Shah2015PrioritySettingExercisesPolicyImplications, VanDerAa2017HealthcareDeservingnessOpinions, JensenPetersen2017DeservingnessHeuristic}.

Intuitive needs rooted in fear of death and the desire to preserve hope also create a vulnerability that can be commercially exploited. In the pharmaceutical sector, one factor to acknowledge is the intervention of well-resourced industry lobbies, capable of deploying costly strategies to pursue and protect their interests \parencite{Greer2016StrengtheningGovernance}. Close ties between pharmaceutical industry and patient organisations are well known, including likely commercially motivated funding pursuits \parencite{Mulinari2020IndustryFundingPatientOrgsSweden, Fabbri2020IndustryFundingPatientOrgs}. These stakeholders share interests in terms of promoting patient access to novel therapies, however, this also creates pathways through which the industry may exert pressure for public funding of new medicines with uncertain value. A more recent concern involves promotion through social media, for example by sponsoring patient influencers \parencite{Mor2024IndustryPromotionSocialMedia}.

Novel cancer medicines entering markets with high uncertainty about effectiveness and safety cannot be meaningfully assessed in terms of cost-effectiveness. Yet stories of dying patients denied ‘last-chance’ interventions tend to resonate strongly with the public, shaping societal expectations about what healthcare ought to provide, regardless of cost or evidence \parencite{PinhoDiasCosta2020MassMediaObstacleRationing, Rubagumya2023MediaCoverageCancerTherapeutics}. In these debates, public payers are often portrayed as ‘the villains,’ preventing patients from reaching the newest innovations that could rescue them from imminent death \parencite{Cohen2017CancerDrugsHighPrice}.

These tensions highlight the need to better understand the mass preferences concerning values that underpin healthcare prioritisation, and how these preferences may be intentionally or unintentionally exploited in favour of commercial stakeholders over societal interests. If healthcare continues to be organised through solidarity-based systems, the challenge lies in determining how such systems can uphold their core values and maintain legitimacy in a context of decreasing public resources, rapidly expanding technological possibilities, rising public expectations and strengthening commercial power.

The experiences of the NHS Cancer Drugs Fund in England provide an illustrative example. The Fund was created in response to public and political pressure to finance new cancer medicines that National Institute of Health and Care Excellence (NICE) had not recommended on the basis of its assessment criteria. An evaluation conducted five years after the establishment of Fund found no meaningful benefit to patients or society, when measured in terms of survival, quality of life, or toxicity, and suggested potential societal harm once opportunity costs were taken into account \parencite{Aggarwal2017CancerDrugsFund}. Thus, while new medications may have brought hope to patients, this hope appeared to a large extent unfounded. Overall, retrospective analyses of novel cancer medicines approved through accelerated access pathways suggest very limited added clinical benefits \parencite{Davis2017EvidenceCancerDrugsEMA, Hwang2020ExpeditedApprovalTherapeuticValue, Brinkhuis2024AddedBenefitRevenues}.

\section{Theoretical framework: prospect theory and the rule of rescue in delegated healthcare}\label{theory}

Prospect theory provides the micro-foundations for understanding how citizens evaluate distributive choices in healthcare rationing and why such evaluations are reference-point dependent. Individuals do not assess outcomes in terms of final states, but as gains and losses relative to a reference point \parencite[263]{Kahneman1979}. The canonical prospect-theoretic value function is concave for gains, convex for losses, and steeper in the loss domain \parencite[342]{Kahneman1984a}, implying diminishing sensitivity and, crucially, loss aversion: losses loom larger than equivalent gains. These regularities remain among the most robust findings in decision research \parencite{Barberis2013}. In the context of healthcare rationing, this implies that the same reimbursement decision can be psychologically represented either as avoiding a loss (not withholding a last-resort option) or as protecting a gain (preserving finite collective resources), and these alternative representations can generate systematically different preferences even when clinical information and costs are held constant.

Reference points are not fixed. They are shaped by expectations and by communicated baselines \parencite{Koszegi2006,Koszegi2007}. In policy environments, where most citizens encounter specialized decisions through mediated communication, the descriptive frame becomes part of how the baseline is constructed: it indicates what is treated as the default and what is treated as a deviation \parencite{Kahneman2003a}. Applied to delegated healthcare rationing, citizens may anchor on multiple plausible baselines: existing coverage norms, a generalized expectation of equal access, an identifiable patient in need, or the collective budget constraint emphasized by expert institutions. The same choice can therefore be interpreted as a departure from an entitlement-like status quo (experienced as a loss) or as a refusal to extend coverage beyond what is fiscally sustainable (experienced as a foregone gain).

Prospect theory also implies a domain-specific pattern of risk-taking. Because the value function is concave over gains and convex over losses, individuals tend to be risk-averse in the gain domain and risk-seeking in the loss domain (the reflection effect) \parencite{Kahneman1979,Vis2011}. This matters directly for high-cost oncology medicines, where decisions often involve clinical uncertainty and the possibility of small-probability benefits at high financial cost. When the situation is framed in the loss domain (for example, as denying a last-resort option), citizens should be more willing to tolerate fiscal risk and uncertainty to avert the salient loss \parencite{Hameleers2021}. When the same situation is framed in the gain domain (for example, as protecting finite resources from extraordinary expenditure and preserving broader access), citizens should become more supportive of restraint \parencite{Hameleers2021}. Related mechanisms reinforce this asymmetry. Probability weighting implies that small probabilities can receive disproportionate attention \parencite{Kahneman1979,Kahneman1984a}; in a rescue-oriented loss frame, even a modest chance of benefit can become politically and morally salient relative to diffuse opportunity costs that remain abstract.

These mechanisms should persist under technocratic delegation because frames operate through interpretation rather than through formal institutional responsibility. Delegation is often narrated as depoliticization: evidence is assessed through objective criteria, thresholds are applied consistently, and distributive choices are presented as technically grounded rather than politically discretionary \parencite{Thatcher2002}. Yet the fact that decisions are justified technically does not immunize publics against reference dependence. Technical criteria themselves must be interpreted, and citizens draw pragmatic inferences about what a communicated rationale implies and what the decision-maker is prioritizing \parencite{Flusberg2024}. Moreover, complexity increases reliance on accessible cues. Under uncertainty, citizens frequently lean on heuristics such as availability, which gives greater weight to vivid, easily imagined cases than to abstract aggregates \parencite{Tversky1973a}. In rationing, the narrative of a specific patient denied a last-resort medicine is cognitively accessible, whereas opportunity costs borne by anonymous others are comparatively opaque. This asymmetry makes it easier for loss frames to dominate public evaluation even when expert institutions supply cost-effectiveness language and probabilistic evidence.

If prospect theory explains why equivalent choices can elicit different preferences depending on the reference point, the rule of rescue clarifies why some reference points acquire exceptional moral force in healthcare. The rule of rescue refers to the perceived imperative to save persons facing avoidable death even when doing so is inefficient and diverts resources from interventions that could generate larger aggregate benefits \parencite[2407]{McKie2003}. It reflects a “shock-horror” response that prioritizes lifesaving over non-lifesaving measures \parencite[2407]{McKie2003}. In rationing contexts, rescue narratives transform a distributive trade-off into an evaluation of whether the state is failing to prevent a preventable loss of life. By foregrounding imminent harm and a morally charged counterfactual (a life that could have been extended), such frames situate citizens in the loss domain, thereby activating the loss aversion and risk-seeking dynamics predicted by prospect theory. Extensions further suggest that end-of-life situations intensify the perceived moral stakes of denial, including concerns about narrative closure \parencite{Sinclair2022a}, which heighten the salience of losses relative to diffuse population-level gains.


Taken together, prospect theory and the rule of rescue provide a coherent account of why technocratic delegation should not eliminate framing effects in public evaluations of reimbursement decisions. When an identical reimbursement decision is framed as avoiding a salient loss to identifiable patients, citizens should be more willing to endorse riskier and more expensive options. When it is framed as preserving collective gains by protecting finite resources, citizens should be more willing to accept restraint. Rescue narratives should magnify the effect of loss framing by intensifying moral salience and by making the focal outcome vivid, concrete, and attributable. %These mechanisms operate at the level of cognition and interpretation, and thus remain active even when decisions are formally insulated from day-to-day electoral accountability and justified through expert procedures. In that sense, technocratic delegation can redistribute political pressure without removing contestation: the struggle shifts toward how decisions are communicated, what reference points are made salient, and whether expert-justified restraint is interpreted as legitimate stewardship or as a failure to rescue.

This implication aligns with research on delegation and accountability, which suggests that delegation may facilitate blame avoidance only under specific institutional conditions and only insofar as citizens accept the attributional story that responsibility has shifted \parencite{Heinkelmann-Wild2023,Heinkelmann-Wild2020}. It also aligns with work on the contestability of expertise, where public acceptance of expert advice depends on more than technical merit and remains vulnerable to competing narratives \parencite{Head2024}. %Accordingly, even in delegated settings, mass preferences over high-cost medicines should remain elastic to loss-versus-gain frames \parencite{Laenen2025}, and frames that activate rescue and loss aversion should systematically shift support toward more permissive funding positions, while stewardship frames should shift support toward conditionality and rejection.

The theoretical framework developed above assumes that formal institutional insulation does not eliminate political contestation; it redirects it toward the arena of public interpretation. This claim benefits from engagement with broader institutional theory on delegation and accountability. Delegation to technically specialized agencies is a common governance strategy in contemporary democracies, reflecting functional demands for expertise as well as political incentives to shift responsibility for contentious decisions. Yet political scientists have questioned whether institutional insulation genuinely depoliticizes decision-making or instead obscures underlying political struggle \parencite{Hanretty2018}. Comparative work suggests that formal independence can improve regulatory quality by enabling more technically sophisticated decisions \parencite{Hanretty2018}. At the same time, such capacity gains do not remove the distributive and value-laden character of decisions with major consequences for affected publics \parencite{Langvatn2022}, and insulation can generate accountability deficits by weakening electoral responsiveness and limiting conventional channels of democratic control \parencite{Crum2017}. %In healthcare, where rationing must reconcile efficiency criteria with legitimacy concerns, these institutional tensions reinforce the central implication of our argument: framing effects persist under technocratic delegation because they operate through reference-dependent cognitive evaluation rather than through formal responsibility alone.


\section{Method}\label{empirics}

The empirical analysis draws on data from the 2021 Finnish Medicines Barometer, a national, cross-sectional population survey administered biennially by the Finnish Medicines Agency to examine experiences, opinions, and values related to health, medicines, and well-being. The 2021 wave included an ad hoc experimental module designed specifically to assess how citizens evaluate expert-justified healthcare funding decisions when identical cases are presented under alternative frames. The survey questionnaire was drafted with influence from previous studies conducted in other countries, in particular the survey by \textcite{Blendon2012}, which similarly exposed citizens to real-life decision-making tasks, and \textcite{Ghinea2021}, which surveyed Australian citizens' attitudes towards public funding of high-cost cancer medicines.

Finland provides an appropriate research context for three reasons. First, the healthcare system is comprehensive and predominantly publicly funded, resembling other advanced welfare states in which questions of healthcare rationing and legitimacy are politically salient \parencite{Keskimaki2019FinlandHiT}. Second, healthcare resource allocation decisions are routinely justified through clinical evidence, cost-effectiveness thresholds, and health technology assessment, making the communicative dimension of these decisions especially important. However, despite the normative emphasis on transparency as a core dimension of legitimate limit-setting, justifications for pharmaceutical reimbursement decisions in Finland are confidential to the public and only communicated to the pharmaceutical company applying for reimbursement status. Third, Nordic healthcare systems face precisely the structural pressures that motivate this study: technological and demographic changes contribute to a widening gap between medical opportunities and fiscal possibilities, which is a common source of controversy among stakeholders.

Data collection was carried out by a professional market research company (Taloustutkimus Ltd) using a pre-recruited online panel of approximately 40,000 Finnish citizens. To reach the target sample size, 10,105 invitations were distributed to panel members. The sample was stratified to ensure balance across gender, age, education level, and geographic region, with eligibility restricted to Finnish-speaking citizens aged 18---79 years. Considering missing data on covariates included in the analysis, the final sample size consists of \Sexpr{formatC(nrow(dat), format = "d", big.mark = ",")} respondents. While online panels are not probability samples, stratification and quota-based recruitment ensure close correspondence with the Finnish adult population on key sociodemographic dimensions, making the data suitable for inference about mass public opinion in a welfare-state context.

The experimental module employed a randomized between-subjects design focused on framing effects. Respondents were randomly assigned to one of three conditions: a control condition and two treatment conditions that varied only in how the decision context was framed. All respondents received an identical clinical vignette describing a new oncology medicine characterized by high cost, uncertain benefit, and limited patient eligibility (\autoref{tab:decision_task}). The vignette was drafted based on a published assessment by the Council for Choices in Health Care in Finland (COHERE Finland), with similar decision options that are used by their recommendations. COHERE, working in conjunction with the Ministry of Social Affairs and Health, only issues recommendations on including or excluding health technologies in the range of public health services. Decisions on reimbursement for outpatient medicines are conducted by the Pharmaceutical Pricing Board, also working in conjunction with the Ministry of Social Affairs and Health, and for inpatient medicines, the ultimate decision lies with hospitals. The framing manipulation consisted solely of additional information presented between the vignette and the decision task, allowing differences in responses to be attributed to framing rather than to substantive informational differences.



% \autoref{tab:decision_task}. Decision-making task administered in the survey with framing manipulation.
\begin{table}[htbp]
\centering
\caption{Decision-making task administered in the survey with framing manipulation.}
\label{tab:decision_task}
\setlength{\tabcolsep}{6pt}
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.2}

\scalebox{0.6}{%
\begin{tabular}{|p{2.1cm}|p{4.2cm}|p{4.2cm}|p{4.2cm}|}
\hline
 & \textbf{Group A (rule-of-rescue frame)} & \textbf{Group B (health maximisation frame)} & \textbf{Group C (control)} \\
\hline
\textbf{Vignette} &
\multicolumn{3}{p{12.6cm}|}{%
\begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\vspace{0pt}
Below, you will find a description of the benefits and costs of a new cancer medicine.\\
Please read the description and then answer the question.\\[0.6em]
There are annually 10 to 20 patients in Finland to whom the new medicine can be prescribed. The medicine does not cure cancer but a laboratory study has shown that it destroys cancer cells in about a third of the patients to whom the new medicine is given. It remains unknown if the new medicine extends patients' lives or if it improves their quality of life. The medicine comes with a great risk of adverse effects. If this new medicine is to be approved for use in Finland, its costs will be over 60.000 euros per patient at the final stage of cancer treatment.
\vspace{0.4em}
\end{minipage}} \\
\hline
\textbf{Frame} &
There is no cure for this particular type of cancer. The new medicine is a possible option for patients who have already received multiple treatments and for whom the remaining options are limited. &
The funds available to healthcare are finite. The adoption of the new medicine means that the funds used to pay for it will mean cuts elsewhere in healthcare. &
None \\
\hline
\textbf{Task} &
\multicolumn{3}{p{12.6cm}|}{%
\begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\vspace{0pt}
What kind of decision regarding the new medicine's use would you find acceptable?\\
Please choose the option that best reflects your opinion.
\begin{enumerate}
  \item The medicine should be adopted to use and paid by the society regardless of the price set on it by the pharmaceutical company
  \item The medicine should be adopted to use and paid by the society if the pharmaceutical company lowers its price
  \item The medicine should not be adopted to use and paid by the society
  \item I don't know
\end{enumerate}
\vspace{0.4em}
\end{minipage}} \\
\hline
\end{tabular}%
}

\end{table}

Following the vignette and framing manipulation, respondents were asked which decision regarding the medicine's use they would find acceptable. Response categories captured increasing levels of cost containment: unconditional public funding, conditional funding tied to price reductions, rejection of funding, and an explicit ``I don't know'' option (n=\Sexpr{as.numeric(table(dat$outcome)["I don't know"])}). These categories map directly onto the theoretical expectations derived from prospect theory, as unconditional funding represents the most risk-acceptant position, conditional funding an intermediate position, and rejection the most risk-averse position.

To estimate the effect of framing on policy preferences, we model respondents' choices using an ordinal logistic regression, reflecting the ordered structure of the outcome variable (\autoref{eq:ordinal_model}).\footnote{As a robustness check, we also estimate a multinomial logit model that relaxes the ordinality assumption. This is useful because, although the substantive response options can be ordered from outright rejection to unconditional public funding, the ``I don't know'' (n=\Sexpr{as.numeric(table(dat$outcome)["I don't know"])}) category is not naturally located on that same underlying scale.} The key independent variable is the framing condition, operationalized as indicators for the rule-of-rescue frame (n=\Sexpr{as.numeric(table(dat$Frame)["Loss (rescue) frame"])}) and the health maximisation (utility-maximizing) frame (n=\Sexpr{as.numeric(table(dat$Frame)["Gains (health maximisation) frame"])}), with the control condition as the reference category (n=\Sexpr{as.numeric(table(dat$Frame)["Control"])}). The specification also includes demographic and socioeconomic covariates commonly associated with healthcare attitudes: gender, age, and income group, as well as indicators capturing health-related exposure, including eligibility for reimbursement of medicines and self-reported medicine expenditures. All models are estimated with survey weights to preserve population representativeness.




Formally, the estimated model can be written as:

\begin{equation}
\Pr(Y_i \leq j) =
\text{logit}^{-1}\!\left(\tau_j
- \beta_1 \,\text{LossRescue}_i
- \beta_2 \,\text{GainsHealthMax}_i
- \boldsymbol{\gamma}\mathbf{X}_i\right),
\label{eq:ordinal_model}
\end{equation}

where $Y_i$ denotes respondent $i$’s preferred funding decision, ordered from outright rejection to unconditional public funding; $\tau_j$ represents the threshold parameters; $\text{LossRescue}_i$ and $\text{GainsHealthMax}_i$ indicate assignment to the loss-framed and gain-framed conditions, respectively; and $\mathbf{X}_i$ is a vector of individual-level covariates (gender, age, income group, region, eligibility for Kela medicine reimbursement, and self-reported medicine expenditure). Thus, \autoref{eq:ordinal_model} estimates how framing shifts the latent propensity to favor more permissive rather than more restrictive funding positions, holding observed characteristics constant and applying survey weights.


