\section{Results}


After fitting \autoref{eq:ordinal_model}, we show \autoref{fig:pred} which presents predicted probabilities for the three principal policy preferences across framing conditions (regression table shown in \autoref{tab:ologit-models}). The results reveal clear and systematic framing effects: respondents exposed to alternative frames shifted their preferred policy responses in substantively meaningful ways.\footnote{The substantive conclusions are broadly similar across the ordinal and multinomial specifications. In both models, the loss (rescue) frame moves respondents toward more permissive funding positions relative to the control condition. The multinomial estimates further suggest that this pattern is concentrated in higher support for conditional and unconditional funding, whereas the gains (health maximisation) frame is weaker overall and is most clearly associated with lower support for unconditional funding.}

\begin{figure}[H]
\caption{Framing Effects on Public Support for Funding a High-Cost Cancer Medicine}\label{fig:pred}
\centering

\scalebox{0.7}{%
\begin{minipage}{\linewidth}
\centering
<<pred, fig.height=5, fig.cap=NULL, echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE>>=

print(pred_plot)

@
\end{minipage}%

}

\vspace{0.25em}
{\footnotesize \textit{Notes:} Points are predicted probabilities from the ordered logistic model (\autoref{eq:ordinal_model}; regression table shown in \autoref{tab:ologit-models}); vertical bars indicate 90\% confidence intervals. The loss (rescue) frame increases support for unconditional funding and reduces outright rejection relative to the control, whereas the gains (health maximisation) frame shifts support toward conditional funding and rejection.}
\end{figure}

The most pronounced pattern concerns support for unconditional public funding, the most risk-seeking option in the decision space. Consistent with the expectations derived from prospect theory, support for unconditional funding increases under the loss frame that emphasizes the absence of alternatives and the proximity of death, and decreases under the gains frame that emphasizes finite budgets and opportunity costs. Conversely, rejection of funding—the most risk-averse response—becomes more likely under the gains frame and less likely under the loss frame. Conditional funding occupies an intermediate position, absorbing shifts in both directions as respondents adjust their evaluations of fiscal risk.

Across conditions, the rank ordering of response options remains stable: conditional funding is consistently most likely, followed by unconditional funding, with outright rejection least likely. What changes is not the rank itself but the level of support attached to each option, as the frames sift probability mass across categories. In particular, the loss frame sifts support upward toward unconditional funding, whereas the gains frame sifts support away from unconditional funding and toward conditional funding and rejection. Thus, framing shifts the level of support across options while preserving the same ordinal structure of preferences.

These results align with the expectation that citizens do not evaluate reimbursement decisions solely in terms of technical information about clinical effectiveness or cost. Instead, preferences vary systematically with the reference point activated by communication (frames). When the decision is presented as avoiding a salient loss to identifiable patients, respondents appear more willing to accept financial risk and clinical uncertainty. When the same decision is presented as protecting existing resources for the broader patient population, respondents become more cautious and more supportive of restraint. The observed shifts are therefore consistent with the reflection effect and loss aversion predicted by prospect theory, as well as with the moral psychology captured by the rule of rescue.

%Importantly, these effects emerge in a setting where respondents are not asked to act as policymakers but to evaluate a decision justified through information resembling real reimbursement debates. This feature of the design speaks directly to the institutional argument advanced in this article. The findings suggest that insulating reimbursement decisions from day-to-day electoral politics and grounding them in technical criteria does not eliminate the role of framing in shaping public evaluation. Citizens remain responsive to how choices are narrated, and their preferences display substantial elasticity even when the informational content of the decision remains constant.

%We believe this elasticity has important implications for the legitimacy and contestability of healthcare rationing. Delegation to expert bodies may reduce direct political responsibility for specific reimbursement decisions, but it does not remove those decisions from the arena of public judgment. Instead, it shifts the locus of contestation toward communication, interpretation, and narrative framing. Public reactions to expert-justified decisions depend not only on the underlying evidence but also on whether the decision is understood as prudent stewardship of collective resources or as a morally troubling failure to rescue.

%Taken together, the results provide empirical support for the theoretical claim developed in the previous section: reference-point–dependent evaluation and rescue-oriented reasoning persist even under institutional arrangements designed to depoliticize distributive choices. In contexts characterized by uncertainty, high stakes, and competing moral logics, framing remains a central mechanism through which citizens interpret and evaluate state action.


\section{Discussion}\label{discussion}

This article examined whether framing effects emerge in mass evaluations of costly reimbursement decisions when those decisions are presented in a technocratic, expert-justified setting---that is, whether citizens' preferences remain reference-point dependent even when the choice context is insulated from electoral politics. Using a population-based survey experiment embedded in the 2021 Finnish Medicines Barometer, we held constant the clinical vignette, uncertainty, and cost information while varying only the interpretive frame attached to an otherwise identical decision. The results indicate substantial and systematic framing effects. Relative to the control condition, the loss (rule-of-rescue) frame shifts respondents toward unconditional public funding and away from outright rejection, whereas the gains (health maximisation) frame increases support for conditionality and rejection. Randomization performed as intended, and model-based predicted probabilities provide a substantively interpretable account of how frames redistribute support across policy options.

These findings support our theoretical claim that technocratic delegation does not neutralize framing effects because framing operates through cognitive evaluation and public interpretation rather than through formal responsibility: even when decisions are presented in technical language and without identifiable patient narratives, citizens’ judgments remain elastic to how the distributive trade-off is framed, so contestation lies in interpretive processes (how decisions are explained and which reference points are made salient). The implications extend to democratic theory, where tensions between expertise and popular sovereignty have long been recognized \parencite{GausLandwehrSchmalzBruns2020}: although delegation is often defended as a means of depoliticizing contentious distributive decisions by placing them in the hands of insulated experts, an alternative perspective suggests that insulation relocates politics from formal arenas of electoral accountability to informal arenas of interpretation. Our results align with this view by indicating that even modest variations in framing generate meaningful shifts in support. Institutional insulation therefore displaces contestation to the communicative domain, where asymmetries in expertise and resources may advantage organized actors over dispersed publics \parencite{Langvatn2022,Eriksen2020PoliticalLiteracy}. This dynamic also intersects with scholarship on expert decision-making in contested policy areas, where governance research emphasizes the importance of ``political literacy’’—recognition that technically justified decisions inevitably embed normative judgments \parencite{Eriksen2020PoliticalLiteracy}: political literacy does not imply partisanship but awareness that regulation frames problems and relies on contestable interpretive concepts \parencite{Eriksen2020PoliticalLiteracy}. In healthcare, where funding decisions necessarily reflect judgments about risk, fairness, and distributive priorities, our findings suggest that expert agencies cannot rely on claims of neutrality alone because legitimacy depends in part on explaining the value commitments implicit in technical reasoning.



Our findings also speak to debates about whether, and to what extent, commonly used prioritisation criteria align with mass preferences, and how far public preferences should in turn guide prioritisation decisions. First, previous studies suggest substantial plurality in mass preferences, including conflicting views and shifts in opinions following deliberation \parencite{vanExel2015QMethodology,ReckersDroog2020CitizensPanel}. Our results align with the view that mass preferences are sensitive to framing \parencite{Desser2013RareDiseaseFraming,Kangas2014}, which complicates the question of how they should guide decision-making when assessed through standard survey instruments.

Second, earlier work suggests considerable public opposition to prioritisation when decisions are explicitly cost-based \parencite{Blendon2012}. In contrast, our results suggest robust support for at least some cost considerations: the modal response in every experimental condition is conditional public funding (i.e., coverage contingent on price reduction). One interpretation is that conditionality is normatively attractive as an intermediate position that reconciles solidarity with demands for price moderation. A complementary interpretation is that it reflects a form of status quo bias toward ``conditional'' compromise positions when choices are uncertain and politically charged \parencite{SamuelsonZeckhauser1988StatusQuoBias} 

{\color{red}This normative appeal of conditionality may reflect framing dynamics identified in prior research. Experimental evidence demonstrates that abstract frames invoking moral sentiments---such as fairness, equity, and solidarity---are substantially more effective at shaping public opinion than frames centered on factual considerations or costs \parencite{Kangas2014}. Moral frames possess what has been termed wider ``valence,'' a measure of emotional attractiveness, such that there is considerably broader agreement on abstract moral principles than on precise factual statements \parencite{Cox2013}. Conditional public funding can be framed to invoke these higher-valence moral sentiments while simultaneously addressing fiscal constraints, thereby creating an intellectually and emotionally compelling middle position. Beyond framing effects, institutional feedback mechanisms may further entrench conditional arrangements as normatively appropriate. Citizens' normative beliefs about policy legitimacy are shaped by the institutional contexts and existing policy designs they experience \parencite{Lindh2015}, through processes whereby welfare institutions themselves constitute and reinforce normative commitments about what counts as just or sustainable \parencite{Svallfors1997}. Where conditional mechanisms are institutionally embedded, this policy feedback effect may render such conditional compromise positions not merely strategically appealing but genuinely normatively resonant with public expectations about how policy should function.}


Evidence from citizen forum designs is consistent with this reading, suggesting that participants may be willing to reject coverage of extremely expensive medicines with limited evidence and may also expect more socially accountable pricing from companies \parencite{Bijlmakers2020CitizenForum}. More broadly, citizen participation in priority-setting has been increasingly pursued, but in heterogeneous ways and with limited evidence on the impact of these initiatives \parencite{Mitton2009ScopingReview, Manafo2018RapidReview, Razavi2020VulnerableParticipation, Oortwijn2021EDPPartII}. Systematic evidence also suggests that meaningful participation requires genuine influence, adequate deliberative conditions, and accessible information \parencite{ArthurSahaKapilashrami2023}.

Relatedly, patient and citizen involvement in prioritisation processes is often motivated by efforts to enhance procedural rather than content legitimacy \parencite{Baltussen2021EDPPartI,Oortwijn2021EDPPartII}. The core rationale is that, because consensus on prioritisation criteria is unlikely, decisions may still be accepted if the process is perceived as fair and legitimate \parencite{Daniels2000AccountabilityReasonableness,DanielsVanDerWilt2016HTADeliberative,BaeroeBaltussen2014LegitimateLimitSetting}. Yet empiric evidence on these mechanisms remains limited. Experimental studies on transparency and legitimacy suggest that the relationship is context-bound and can yield both positive and negative effects \parencite{deFineLicht2014PolicyArea, deFineLichtNaurin2014TransparencyLegitimacy, deFineLicht2020JanusTransparency}.

Moreover, real-world rationing debates rarely occur under neutral framing conditions. Competing narratives are advanced by organized interests with unequal communicative resources. The pharmaceutical industry, patient advocacy organizations, professional associations, and public authorities deploy frames strategically to shape interpretation \parencite{Sell2004}. Industry lobbying exceeds \$233 million annually in the United States, alongside political engagement and advocacy funding \parencite{Steinbrook2020}. Funded patient organizations frequently participate in coordinated campaigns amplifying rescue-oriented narratives \parencite{Parker2019}, within broader patterns of industry support documented across contexts \parencite{Parker2019,Fabbri2020IndustryFundingPatientOrgs,Mulinari2020IndustryFundingPatientOrgsSweden}. Given the emotional salience of rescue frames in life-threatening conditions, such asymmetries may influence public evaluations of identical evidence. This does not imply that framing is inherently manipulative; rather, it underscores that delegated governance operates within competitive interpretive environments. Institutional safeguards may therefore need to address communicative balance in addition to procedural rigor \parencite{Gabe2012HerceptinCountervailingPowers}.

Several limitations qualify these conclusions. First, the study relies on a single-country sample and a single policy domain, limiting external validity across institutional contexts and disease areas. Cross-national work suggests similar plurality of views across European publics, albeit with differences in the specific positions expressed \parencite{vanExel2015QMethodology}. Finland has also been criticized from within for the lack of explicit prioritisation, while neighboring Nordic countries (notably Sweden and Norway) are more often described as pioneers in articulating national prioritisation principles \parencite{Cappelen2022ResponsibilityNorway, Torkki2022PrioritizationFinland}. Future research could therefore examine whether framing effects are comparable across these institutional settings and assess whether more explicit prioritisation criteria condition perceived legitimacy. Second, the experiment employs a single vignette configuration; framing effects may vary with uncertainty type, budget impact, or perceived deservingness. Third, treatments are brief, which enhances internal validity but may not capture repeated exposure to emotionally saturated messaging or elite cues. Fourth, the outcome is attitudinal rather than behavioral, so downstream political consequences are inferred rather than observed. Finally, although the ordinal logit framework appropriately models ordered responses, psychological mediators such as perceived loss magnitude or moral obligation were not directly measured.

These limitations suggest a focused research agenda. Future studies should examine heterogeneity in framing sensitivity, given that reference points may vary with political trust, system satisfaction, illness exposure, redistribution attitudes, or policy knowledge. Attribution and accountability mechanisms should also be manipulated directly, varying who is said to decide and what procedural safeguards are emphasized. Comparative experiments contrasting technocratic framing with patient-story framing would clarify whether delegation dampens or merely displaces the persuasive force of identifiable beneficiaries. Finally, longitudinal and field designs could assess persistence, learning, and real-world political consequences.

Overall, the evidence suggests that even under technocratic delegation, distributive healthcare decisions remain politically consequential because citizens evaluate them through reference-dependent interpretive frames. Delegation may reduce overt partisan conflict over particular reimbursement decisions, but it does not eliminate the cognitive and moral structures through which rationing is judged. Rather, it shifts contestation toward how expert justifications are framed and which reference points communication renders salient.


